<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Man Implicates Uncle in Attempt To Smuggle Heroin to Saudi Arabia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0252E Peshawar MASHRIQ in Urdu 11 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0252E </F>
<F P=104>  Peshawar MASHRIQ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [News Report: "Accused Admits Smuggling Drugs to Saudi </F>
Arabia"] 
  [Text] Peshawar (Staff Reporter)--Mohammed Hanif son of 
Itaul Rehman has exposed the black deeds of his uncle who sends 
naive villagers with heroin to Saudi Arabia falsely promising 
them wealth and jobs. The Narcotics Police had presented the 
accused in Magistrate Afsar Khan's court after initial 
questioning and the accused admitted in the court that his uncle 
Rehman was a fisherman in Karachi until recently. His luck 
changed and he went to Saudi Arabia and earned money as a driver 
in addition to working as a fisherman. The accused further said 
that his uncle upon his return home started the business of 
sending people abroad. He had already sent nine villagers to 
Arab countries. His uncle had arranged for 19 persons including 
his nephew to go abroad. He charged each person 30,000 rupees. 
The accused said that his uncle had prepared him to go with the 
other persons. One sack full of floating balls used for fishing 
were given to every two persons to carry with them. The names of 
these persons were written on those sacks to help pass the 
customs check points. His other uncle also had come to see them 
all off. At the airport the floating balls were found to be 
filled with heroin and all of these people were arrested. The 
accused said that they were innocent and that his uncle had 
deceived all the passengers as he owned that heroin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

