<F P=101> ALBANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Italy, EU To Finance Environmental Joint Project in Shkoder </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701201094 Tirana ATA in English 1126 GMT 27 Jan 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2701201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, January 27 (ATA) -- A joint 
Italian-Albanian environmental protection project with 
headquarters in Shkoder began operation in December 1993. The 
objective of the project is the protection of the environment of 
the city, famous for its cultural and historical interest, 
including its excellent museum. The project will also have an 
education component. Thus far the "Lvia" Project has 690 
employees. They are engaged in reforestation in the hills round 
the city, the improvement of roads, restoration of the "Rozafa" 
Castle, as well as work on hospitals, schools, libraries, and 
the city's museum. 
  "There is a good beginning," the director of Caritas for 
north Albania, Gjon Markagjoni, told ATA, adding that in the 
future the project will also cover the district of [word 
indistinct] and the communes of Lac and Vau i Dejes. The 
additional activity will increase the number of the workers by 
several hundred. 
  Three billion lira have been allocated by Italian bishoprics 
and the Italian Government to this joint undertaking. This sum 
will finance the Lvia Project for only several months, but, 
according to Markagjoni, the European Union will contribute to 
that project in the near future. The EU financing will permit 
the employment of additional workers and an expansion of project 
activities. Angjelin Muzhani, a Caritas representative, said 
that future plans for the project will also cover agriculture, 
especially vineyards. 

</TEXT>

