<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Refuses To Join Ban on Nuclear Waste Dumping in Seas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202192994 Moscow RIA in English 1638 GMT 22 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2202192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 22, RIA -- An agreement banning the 
dumping of radioactive and industrial waste in the seas came 
into force on February 21, 1994. It was signed by 70 countries. 
  Russia has, however, officially announced it is not going to 
join this agreement. 
  Sada Aksartova, a spokeswoman for the international 
ecological organisation Greenpeace, in commenting on the Russian 
Federation's stand, told a RIA correspondent it was a great 
mistake on the part of the Russian Government, and will evoke a 
highly negative response from the other countries. 
  Among the major powers, according to Aksartova, only 
Australia, in addition to Russia, has refused to accede to the 
agreement, "taking time-out" for two years. 

</TEXT>

