<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Commissioner Rebukes UK Over Water Quality Estimate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1102143294 London FINANCIAL TIMES in English 11 Feb 94 p 7 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM1102143294 </F>
<F P=104>  London FINANCIAL TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by environment correspondent Bronwen Maddox: </F>
"Rebuke From EU on Water Estimate"] 
  [Text] The UK has overestimated the costs of complying 
with water quality directives, Mr Ioannis Paleokrassas, the 
union's environment commissioner, said in London yesterday. 
  UK water companies have predicted that they will need to 
invest more than 10bn pounds to bring water and sewage treatment 
standards in line with the EU [European Union] urban waste water 
directive. But Mr Paleokrassas, whose officials met UK water 
regulators Ofwat and the National Rivers Authority this week, 
said the eventual costs were likely to be "several billion 
pounds" lower. 
  His comments came after months of rising tension between 
London and Brussels over water standards. The UK has attacked 
some standards as unnecessarily high, and asked for more time to 
comply. Yesterday Mr Paleokrassas said: "There will be no 
lowering of standards or lengthening of dates." 
  Thames Water said: "A lot of investment follows from this 
directive, but the costings are complex and the interpretation 
needs to be clarified further." 
  Speaking at the London School of Economics, Mr Paleokrassas 
also said the European Commission would say within two weeks 
whether the UK government's decision to licence the Thorp 
nuclear reprocessing plant at Sellafield followed commission 
rules. 
  "There is some doubt as to whether the environmental impact 
assessment has been infringed," he said. 

</TEXT>

