<H3> <TI>   Five Member States Adopt Plan To Fight Against Pollution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3101102994 Brussels EUROPE in English 28 Jan 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3101102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Five of Twelve Adopt European Plan </F>
To Fight Against Pollution and Reinforce Maritime Safety"; as 
released by Brussels Textline database] 
  [Text] The ministers of five EC countries (Germany, 
Belgium, France, Great Britain and the Netherlands) adopted, on 
Wednesday [26 January] evening in Paris, a plan to improve 
maritime safety and reduce pollution. According to a communique 
published on Thursday by the French Transport Ministry, the plan 
concerns the following five points for action: 
  - reinforcement of the fight against "substandard" ships; 
  - the obligation to have markings/signalings in the 
Channel/North Sea zone; 
  - immediate application of container stowing regulations by 
the International Maritime Organization [IMO]; 
  - maximum safety requirements for passenger transport; 
  - reinforcement of means of intervention. 
  The communique stresses, moreover, that the five countries 
concerned "are ready to act together in London with the IMO and 
in Brussels with the European Union". 

</TEXT>

